{
  "texts": [
    "So, the Americans:",
    "'should be protected from unsafe or ineffective systems, should not face discrimination by algorithms and systems should be used and designed in an equitable way, should be protected from abusive data practices via built-in protections and should have agency over how their data is used, should know that an automated system is being used and understand how and why it contributes to outcomes that impact them, should be able to opt out, where appropriate, and have access to a person who can quickly consider and remedy problems they encounter' (The White House, 2022).",
    "The Blueprint for an AI Bill of Rights is addressed to companies and government authorities, who are advised to implement the five principles in their policy regarding the development and use of AI.",
    "Although it can be considered a legislative act that takes an important step towards protecting the fundamental rights of US citizens (Park, 2023, p. 27), having no binding power could determine the private sector to simply ignore it (Hine & Floridi, 2023, p. 285).",
    "One year later, on October 30, 2023, the Biden administration adopted the Executive Order on the Safe, Secure, and Trustworthy Development and Use of Artificial Intelligence (The White House, 2023)."
  ]
}